<para id="fs-idm46146656">In a raffle, there are 250 prizes of $5, 50 prizes of $25, and 10 prizes of $100. Assuming that 10,000 tickets are to be issued and sold, what is a fair price to charge to break even?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idp37641408">
<para id="fs-idp31192112">Let <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis> = the amount of money to be won on a ticket. The following table shows the PDF for <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis>:
<table id="fs-idm110559056" summary="A two column, five row table is shown. The header row contains x, and p opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis. The first data row contains 0 and 0.969. The second data row contains 5 and two hundred fifth over ten thousand equals 0.025. The third data row contains 25 and fifth over ten thousand equals 0.005. The final data row contains 100 and 10 over ten thousand equals 0.001.">
<tgroup cols="2">
<colspec colnum="1" colname="c1"/>
<colspec colnum="2" colname="c2"/>

<thead>
<row>
<entry><emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis></entry>
<entry><emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>(<emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis>)</entry>
</row>
</thead>
<tbody>
<row><entry>0</entry><entry>.969</entry></row>
<row><entry>5</entry><entry>
<m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mfrac>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>250</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>10,000</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math> = .025</entry></row>
<row><entry>25</entry><entry><m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mfrac>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>50</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>10,000</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math> = .005</entry></row>
<row><entry>100</entry><entry><m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mfrac>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>10</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mtext>10,000</m:mtext>
   </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>

 </m:mrow>
</m:math> = .001</entry></row>
</tbody>
</tgroup>
</table>
</para><para id="fs-idm41233712">Calculate the expected value of <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis>.</para>
<para id="fs-idm86179776">0(.969) + 5(.025) + 25(.005) + 100(.001) = .35</para>
<para id="fs-idm45715696">A fair price for a ticket is $0.35. Any price over $0.35 will enable the lottery to raise money.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>

